body:

Onnxruntime raises SIGSEGV signal on loading the quantized model.

**Urgency**

**To Reproduce**
Google Colab [link](https://colab.research.google.com/drive/1mk9b-_5dlAiSsMYqWvxcYfqxjhi4juRq) for reproduction.
Github Gist [link](https://gist.github.com/vuvko/e5fa172387f9a12b6936e8505cded394) for the reference ([model file](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1HJP28RcVym3bj70pK_k4LMUQnBj6uoQN)).
Run all cells for the colab notebook, or run the script from Gist with a saved model file as `model_q.onnx`.

**Expected behavior**
Expected to see an `input0` to be printed (it's an input layer's name).

**Additional context**
The original model is a modified face detector in PyTorch ([params file](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1Ni8WfR1gdhvz-T2fdfuC5gc_E_7xo6B3)). It was converted using `torch.onnx._export` ([converted model](https://drive.google.com/open?id=1lje7hI0Eiatk_SjHGk5lyjADQU-YMVMG)). The converted model can be used as it is but after quantization with [quantization tool](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/tree/master/onnxruntime/python/tools/quantization) it cannot be loaded with onnxruntime.

This was tested on google colab, and ArchLinux machine (python 3.8, gcc 9.3, building from source and binary provided by PyPi). 
Running this with gdb shows this stack:
```
[New Thread 0x7fffe2ffd700 (LWP 669857)]
[New Thread 0x7fffe27fc700 (LWP 669858)]
[New Thread 0x7fffe1ffb700 (LWP 669859)]
[New Thread 0x7fffe17fa700 (LWP 669860)]
[New Thread 0x7fffe0ff9700 (LWP 669861)]

Thread 1 "python" received signal SIGSEGV, Segmentation fault.
onnxruntime::DequantizeLinear<unsigned char>::Compute (this=0x55555607f5e0, 
    ctx=0x7fffffffc5b0)
    at /home/andrey/libs/onnxruntime/include/onnxruntime/core/framework/tensor_shape.h:47
47	    return std::vector<int64_t>::operator[](static_cast<int>(idx));

```

I tested loading other quantized models, and everything works with [resnet50_v1](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/onnxruntime/python/tools/quantization/E2E_example_model/resnet50_v1.onnx) model.

title: Fix race condition creating ConverterResourceStore
body:
**Description**: Creating ConverterResourceStore in parallel sessions in the same device leads to a race condition when both threads overwrite the same ConverterResourceStore shared_prt (which is undefined behavior). To repro, run the MultiThreadMultiSession or MultiThreadMultiSessionGpu test multiple times (keep it looping and it should crash in about 40 min to 1:30).

Bug will show as the old shared_ptr value being destroyed when overwritten by the other thread. Acessing the old ConverterResourceStore will either segfault, call abort() with `d:\agent\_work\8\s\src\vctools\crt\github\stl\src\mutex.cpp(165): unlock of unowned mutex`, or with `d:\agent\_work\8\s\src\vctools\crt\github\stl\src\mutex.cpp(64): mutex destroyed while busy`

Related:

* https://microsoft.visualstudio.com/OS/_sprints/taskboard/WinML/OS/2004/2004-1?workitem=25822488
* https://dev.azure.com/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/_build/results?buildId=128539&view=results

Quote:

> A shared_ptr instance can be "read" (accessed using only const operations) simultaneously by multiple threads. **Different** shared_ptr instances can be "written to" (accessed using mutable operations such as operator= or reset) simultaneously by multiple threads (even when these instances are copies, and share the same reference count underneath.)
**Any other simultaneous accesses result in undefined behavior.**

title: Use MlasConv for 1D convolutions
body:
**Description**: Use the existing 2D convolution code in MlasConv to also handle 1D convolutions. This avoids the overhead of the generic ND im2col path as well as inheriting the threaded im2col implementation.

**Motivation and Context**
This improves the situation described in #3418. That model now runs with the same performance as an equivalent model using 2D convolutions with "-o 2". Internally, MLAS just runs the convolution as a 2D convolution with height=1. On one AVX2 system running single-threaded, old was 900+ms, new was 225ms.

Using "-o 99", a 2D model can still run faster thanks to the NCHWc layout optimizer. This optimizer does not support reordering 1D tensors. With NCHWc, execution time drops to 185ms.

title: QuantizeLinear saturates to wrong range for int8
body:
**Describe the bug**
QuantizeLinear satures to [-127, 127] for int8.
According to the specification, it satures to [-128, 127].

**Urgency**
None.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Ubuntu 18.04.4 LTS
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.2.0
- Python version: 3.6.9
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): N/A
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): N/A
- CUDA/cuDNN version: 10.1/7.6
- GPU model and memory: GeForce RTX 2080Ti 11GB x2

**To Reproduce**
Run the following code:
```
import numpy as np
import onnx
import onnxruntime
from onnx import helper
from onnx import TensorProto

x = helper.make_tensor_value_info('x', TensorProto.FLOAT, ['N'])
scale = helper.make_tensor_value_info('scale', TensorProto.FLOAT, [])
zero_point = helper.make_tensor_value_info('zero_point', TensorProto.INT8, [])
y = helper.make_tensor_value_info('y', TensorProto.INT8, ['N'])
node = helper.make_node(
    'QuantizeLinear',
    ['x', 'scale', 'zero_point'],
    ['y'],
)
graph = helper.make_graph(
    [node],
    'model',
    [x, scale, zero_point],
    [y],
)
model = helper.make_model(graph)
onnx.save(model, 'model.onnx')

session = onnxruntime.InferenceSession('model.onnx')
result = session.run(['y'], {
    'x': np.array([-129, -128, -127, -126, 126, 127, 128, 129], np.float32),
    'scale': np.array(1, np.float32),
    'zero_point': np.array(0, np.int8),
})
print(result)
```

Result:
```
[array([-127, -127, -127, -126,  126,  127,  127,  127], dtype=int8)]
```

**Expected behavior**
```
[array([-128, -128, -127, -126,  126,  127,  127,  127], dtype=int8)]
```

**Screenshots**
None.

**Additional context**
None.

title: Definition of Im2col<T, StorageOrder::NHWC> does not take into account groups attribute
body:
**Describe the bug**
The definition of `void Im2col<float, StorageOrder::NHWC>` in `math_cpu.cc` is incorrect, as it does not seem to take into account the number of `groups`, as seen in the Caffe implementation [here](https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/blob/master/caffe2/quantization/server/im2col_dnnlowp.h#L186) (or alternatively [here](https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/blob/master/caffe2/utils/math_cpu.cc#L2383) – I am not sure what the difference in performance is between the two versions). Since it is not used anywhere (as all of onnx's operators are nchw, unless of course you define your own custom operator), it can be removed entirely if it is deemed a wontfix.

As a tangential question/clarification, I was wondering why the calls to `Im2Col` in the implementation of `QLinearConv` and `ConvInteger` are done repeatedly inside the inner loop of `for (int group_id = 0; group_id < conv_attrs_.group; ++group_id)`. If you look at the definition of [Caffe2/PyTorch's CPU conv operator](https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/blob/master/caffe2/operators/conv_op_impl.h#L97) they perform the im2col for the entire series of groups at once, which seems like it might potentially improve performance.

**Urgency**
P3/P4, as it does not affect any existing features

**Expected behavior**
`void Im2col<float, StorageOrder::NHWC>` should either be removed entirely or fixed (preferably the latter, as custom operators might want to use NHWC layout and having an existing implementation avoids re-inventing the wheel).

`ConvInteger`/ `QLinearConv` seems like it could potentially be improved by performing the im2col for the entire batch of `group_id` at once. Although I am not too familiar with this area, so there might be a reason why this was deemed infeasible.

title: Example for Handling ONNXType other than ONNX_TYPE_TENSOR
body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
I have a program using the C library of ORT, which assumes the ONNX model's I/O are always type Tensor, but I encountered one model converted from sklearn that has output type `sequence<map<int64,float32>>`. I saw that there were APIs regarding sequence and map type, so I wonder if there are examples to handle such I/O? i.e. running the model and retrieving the output.

**Additional context**
The model is a simple logistic regression:
```Python
from sklearn.datasets import load_iris
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression, LogisticRegression
from skl2onnx import convert_sklearn
from skl2onnx.common.data_types import FloatTensorType
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression, LogisticRegression
import numpy as np

iris = load_iris()
X, y = iris.data, iris.target
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y)

logr = LogisticRegression()
fake_y = (X_train[:, 0] > 5.2).astype("int")
logr.fit(X_train, fake_y)

initial_type = [('float_input', FloatTensorType([None, 4]))]
onx = convert_sklearn(logr, initial_types=initial_type)
with open("logr.onnx", "wb") as f:
    f.write(onx.SerializeToString())
```

title: Fix output range for int8_t QuantizeLinear op
body:
**Description**: This updates the output range for QuantizeLinear to be -128..127 instead of -127..127. This addresses the problem raised in #3442.

**Motivation and Context**
The original implementation of QuantizeLinear used -127..127 and this was carried forward to MLAS and now the CUDA kernels. The ONNX specification of the operator states that the range should be -128..127. The nGraph EP was already using the correct range.

title: Update Graph SetInputs and SetOutputs for training

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
**Description**
Fix training modification of Graph SetInputs() and SetOutputs(). Originally there were distinct code paths in Graph based on whether the graph was loaded from a GraphProto or created from scratch. The training modifications made that distinction a bit ambiguous - i.e., even though the Graph is loaded from a GraphProto for training, sometimes we rely on the other code path, e.g., to deduce the graph inputs after modifying it. Consequently, there was some odd behavior when using SetInputs(). For correctness, this change separates the cases where the graph is loaded from a GraphProto and where it is created from scratch.

**Motivation and Context**
- Address PR comment: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/3174#discussion_r397042400
- Fix odd behavior in Graph::SetInputs()

title: Handle optional inputs and remove more empty shape nodes in TensorRT EP
body:
- Remove optional inputs at (sub)graph level
   When TRT EP partitions a graph for TRT, optional input of operators become subgraph's input, which will cause problem since it doesn't have name/type/values. This PR removed optional inputs from subgraph input list.
- Exclude empty shape related nodes from TRT subgraph
   TRT doesn't support empty shape in current release. When a model has Nonzero op, there is a chance that Nonzero's output has empty shape during runtime. This mostly happened in RCNN models. As a workaround this PR excluded empty shape related nodes from TRT subgraph. New TRT release 7.1 will fix the issue and support empty shape.

title: Update Attention operator for GPT2
body:
**Description**: 

Add unidirectional attribute for GPT2. 

The mask is with shape (S, S), where S is the sequence length. Only lower triangle will be used like
[[1, 0, 0]
 [1, 1, 0]
 [1, 1, 1]]
In cuda operator, only the first i elements are used in softmax calculation (the remaining elments will get 0.0 after softmax). num_valid for i-th row is i.

In cpu operator, the upper triangle of mask matrix is filled with -10000 like the following:
[[0, -10000, -10000],
 [0,   0,        -10000]
 [0,    0         0        ]]
It is added to GEMM result so that the elements with -10000 will get 0.0 after softmax.
When mask is unidirectional, mask_index shall not be in input.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

The mask in GPT2 is unidirectional (left-to-right): Current word can only attend to previous words on the left. Add this change to support GPT2 model.

**Description**: This is required for running multithreaded with multi-GPUs.

**Motivation and Context**
Add a Python API for specifying the random seed to onnxruntime, to match other frameworks, e.g.
`numpy.random.seed(<seed>)`
`torch.manual_seed(<seed>) / torch.cuda.manual_seed(<seed>)`

The `ort_trainer.py` was generating random samples directly on CUDA.  CUDA does not guarantee the same random sequence gets generated on different devices (even with the same seed).  Instead, we will generate the random sequence on CPU and move it to the device.

title: Fork the WinML APIs into the Microsoft namespace
body:
Issues: The current WinML redist implementation is under the Windows namespace. This collides with the Windows namespace in the Inbox SDK, causing developers to do activation hooking, and include path shenanigans. 

Fix: Fork the WinML APIs into the Microsoft namespace. These APIs will be kept in sync with the Windows namespace, but will not collide with the inbox sdk implementation headers/metadata.

1.	Add CMake flag to enable Microsoft namespace, onnxruntime_BUILD_WINML_IN_MICROSOFT_NS. The Default value is OFF in CMake, but is set to ON in build.py. This has the effect of all ORT builds to build into Microsoft, and inbox WinML to build into Windows by default.
2.	Update idl files with macro to toggle namespace.
3.	Build raw headers from midl with /ns_prefix for Microsoft. Redist build, and without for Windows. Inbox build. This is because we ship the raw headers in the SDK and should not generate ns_prefix.
4.	Need to organize namespacealiases combine winrt::Microsoft::* and winrt::Windows::*
5.	Need to remove all usage of winrt::Windows in favor of namespace aliases (or macros in some cases) in implementation.
6.	Need to rename the dll to Microsoft.* in redist builds.
7.	Need to remove all usage of winrt::Windows in favor of namespace aliases (or macros in some cases) in tests.
8.	Need to update nuget package to reference dll, libs, pdbs, metadata and headers with Microsoft.* and not Windows*.
9.	Need to update nuget package to include dualapipartition.h.

title: Python install requires
body: This PR ties the `requirements.txt` file directly to `install_requires` in `setup.py`. This is aimed at making it easier to keep the versions up to date, and to avoid either place getting stale. title: Error in Trying to Use TensorRT Backend with ONNX Model
body:
**Describe the bug**
I've been using Triton Inference Server with an ONNX model that has worked correctly, and continues to work correctly. I tried to switch over to using the TensorRT Execution Provider and received the following error:

```Unsupported ONNX data type: BOOL (9)```

I created an issue in Triton's project as well, but this seems like it may be coming from the runtime and not the inference server itself:

https://github.com/NVIDIA/triton-inference-server/issues/1301

For context - I took a model from the transformers library (XLMRobertaForTokenClassification), converted that into ONNX, and then tried to switch over to using the TensorRT execution provider. 

**Urgency**
No hard deadlines and not urgent.

**System information**
- Triton Inference Server Container - version py3-20.03
- GPU model and memory: T4/16GB

**To Reproduce**
- Convert the XLMRobertaForTokenClassification into ONNX
- Try and run it in Triton using the TensorRT Execution Provider instead of CUDA

**Expected behavior**
I expect it to convert without an error. In general I understand not all operations may be supported, but I was surprised to see an error being thrown on a BOOL datatype.

title: Add int64 input type for ReduceProd
body:
**Description**:
Adding int64 input type for ReduceProd

**Motivation and Context**
This input type is required for exporting numel op.
Numel op applies ReduceProd on the output of the Shape node. Output of the Shape node is always of type int64, which is expected since it represents sizes.

Numel is a frequently used operator that's used in torchvision models Mask RCNN and Keypoint RCNN.

title: Fix crash in DequantizeLinear with scalar tensor
body:
**Description**: This fixes the crash describe in #3417 where a scalar tensor crashes in the DequantizeLinear kernel.

**Motivation and Context**
The kernel for DequantizeLinear is shared between the official ONNX definition of the operator and an older contrib op version that supported an axis attribute with some broadcasting semantics. The crash was caused by not checking if the axis value as valid to use. The model from #3417 is now able to load and run and additional unit tests were added for the scalar case.

Also cleaned up the kernel registration to use the type constraints instead of explicitly listing parameter names in order to reduce code size.
